05628nam a22009255i 9780823299829DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232998297 a10.1515/97808232998292doi  a(DE-B1597)624075  a(OCoLC)1318948208  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR590b.M396 2022 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a821/.709145223/eng/202204281 aMcGrath, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLook Round for Poetry :bUntimely Romanticisms /cBrian McGrath. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLit Z00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Understating Poetry -- t2. The Poetics of Downturns -- t3. I Wandered Lonely as an iCloud -- t4. On the Poetry of Posthumous Election -- t5. Keats for Beginners -- t6. The Grammar of Romanticism: Shelley’s Prepositions -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tSeries Editors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPoetry is dead. Poetry is all around us. Both are trite truisms that this book exploits and challenges.In his 1798 Advertisement to Lyrical Ballads, William Wordsworth anticipates that readers accustomed to the poetic norms of the day might not recognize his experiments as poems and might signal their awkward confusion upon opening the book by looking round for poetry, as if seeking it elsewhere. Look Round for Poetry transforms Wordsworth’s idiomatic expression into a methodological charge. By placing tropes and figures common to Romantic and Post-Romantic poems in conjunction with contemporary economic, technological, and political discourse, Look Round for Poetry identifies poetry’s untimely echoes in discourses not always read as poetry or not always read poetically.Once one begins looking round for poetry, McGrath insists, one might discover it in some surprising contexts. In chapters that spring from poems by Wordsworth, Lucille Clifton, John Keats, and Percy Bysshe Shelley, McGrath reads poetic examples of understatement alongside market demands for more; the downturned brow as a figure for economic catastrophe; Romantic cloud metaphors alongside the rhetoric of cloud computing; the election of the dead as a poetical, and not just a political, act; and poetic investigations into the power of prepositions as theories of political assembly.For poetry to retain a vital power, McGrath argues, we need to become ignorant of what we think we mean by it. In the process we may discover critical vocabularies that engage the complexity of social life all around us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish poetryy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLyric poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoetryxAppreciation. 0aRomanticismzEngland. 4aCinema & Media Studies. 4aDigital Culture. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aJohn Keats.  aLucille Clifton.  aPercy Bysshe Shelley.  aWilliam Wordsworth.  afigure.  apoetry.  aromanticism.  atrope.  auntimeliness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFord